Intermediate Trade: US Steel


By
Skip Raschke


         | Jul 19, 2017 | 8:30 AM EDT      



           
 The Trade: Buy 1 X 
 September 25 call and sell 1 X 
 September 30 call for a 1.00 point debit. 
 

    
 

    
 

  United States Steel Corporation 
 (X)  has seen a low of $16 and a high of $42 (both rounded) in the past 52 wild weeks of trading. 
 

    
 

  The stock of this 116-year-old company has a seriously high beta of 4. So this trade setup should be considered as volatile as any underlying stock can be. 
 

    
 

  Fundamentally, X trades with a forward price-to-earnings ratio of 13x. In today's nosebleed P/E arena, a 13x P/E is inexpensive -- if not cheap. 
 

    
 

  There has been talk in D.C. and Wall Street that POTUS Trump might impose tariffs on foreign steel sold in the U.S. If that were to become a reality, odds highly favor the U.S. steel sector -- and presumably X -- rallying sharply. If not, X still is trading at a rather modest forward P/E of just 13. 
 

    
 

  The trade tactic I prefer now for X is the bullishly biased, 100% risk-controlled, out-of-the-money vertical call spread expiring in September. 
 

    
 
 
 The trade is as follows: Buy 1 X 
 September 25 call and sell 1 X 
 September 30 call for a 1.00 point debit. The suggested target to close for a gain is a bid of $1.50 and the suggested target to stop out the trade is a bid of $0.50. Best to scale into the position using limit orders. 
        



